					<dt class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="comment-1972">
<span class="avatar"><a href="http://www.privacycrisis.com" rel="nofollow"></a></span>
<span class="comment_num"><a href="#comment-1972" title="Permalink to this comment" rel="nofollow">6</a></span>
<span class="comment_author"><a href="http://www.privacycrisis.com" onclick="javascript:_gaq.push(['_trackEvent','outbound-commentauthor','http://www.privacycrisis.com']);"  rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Grant Hall</a></span>
<span class="comment_time">April 10, 2012 at 11:06 pm</span>

					</dt>
					<dd class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
<div class="format_text" id="comment-body-1972">
<p>Bill,<br />
Enjoyed your site as well as the video.</p>
<p>During my quest to secure financial privacy, I spent substantial time researching and traveling, and concluded it&#8217;s all about persistence and communication, and knowing what one requires prior to making privacy requests to given institutions.</p>
<p>I found check cashing stores amenable to my requests for privacy and they offered two important financial privacy options: check cashing-the old fashioned cash and carry money away system, and the use of their sponsor banks for nontraditional though functional bank accounts. One method or both methods can be used to gain banking secrecy and one&#8217;s communication and resources are very important. I found it was possible to have total banking secrecy in the U.S.A. though it took a good deal of time, persistence. Hence Privacy Crisis Banking: Bank Secrecy Plan &amp; Resource Guide to Protect Identity, Money, and Property.</p>
<p>Bitcoin is an interesting concept. Tell me more about it, please. Do you payment processing difficult?</p>
<p>Thanks.</p>
<p>Grant Hall</p>
</div>
